<self-uri xlink:href="http://www.scielo.br/scielo.php?script=sci_arttext&amp;pid=S0103-20701995000100163&amp;lng=en&amp;nrm=iso"></self-uri><self-uri xlink:href="http://www.scielo.br/scielo.php?script=sci_abstract&amp;pid=S0103-20701995000100163&amp;lng=en&amp;nrm=iso"></self-uri><self-uri xlink:href="http://www.scielo.br/scielo.php?script=sci_pdf&amp;pid=S0103-20701995000100163&amp;lng=en&amp;nrm=iso"></self-uri><abstract abstract-type="short" xml:lang="pt"><p><![CDATA[Foucault pensou o papel do intelectual na contesta&#231;&#227;o a Sartre e aos pressupostos do engagement, em especial os associados &#224; filosofia da consci&#234;ncia e ao humanismo. Depois de 1968, por&#233;m, quando os fundamentos pol&#237;ticos do sartrismo desabavam - em particular a proximidade do Partido Comunista - Sartre p&#244;de fazer causa comum com Foucault, ao mesmo tempo que este assumia, de boa ou m&#225; vontade, pap&#233;is que sempre negara, como o da voz p&#250;blica.]]></p></abstract>
<abstract abstract-type="short" xml:lang="en"><p><![CDATA[Foucault reflected upon the role of the intellect by contesting Sartre and the pressupositions of the engagement, especially the ones associated to the philosophy of conscience and humanism. After 1968, however, when the political bases of sartrism crumbled - particularly the proximity of the Communist Party -, Sartre could make common force with Foucault at the same time the latter assumed, willing of not, roles he had always refused, as the one of being a public voice.]]></p></abstract>
